00:00:23,880 --> 00:00:24,800
The Headlines:

2
00:00:25,440 --> 00:00:27,240
Authorities have devised a solution

3
00:00:27,240 --> 00:00:29,800
to prevent future MRT breakdowns.

4
00:00:30,520 --> 00:00:32,280
Slash, slash, slash.

5
00:00:32,560 --> 00:00:35,960
Singapore’s retrenchment rate
has hit a seven-year high.

6
00:00:36,880 --> 00:00:39,800
And one policeman
speaks out against the trend

7
00:00:39,800 --> 00:00:42,400
of handsome police spokespersons.

8
00:00:54,640 --> 00:00:56,280
Hello and welcome to The Noose.

9
00:00:56,280 --> 00:00:57,520
I’m B.B.See.

10
00:00:58,000 --> 00:00:59,440
And I’m Xin Hua Hua.

11
00:00:59,680 --> 00:01:00,960
Hey ladies,

12
00:01:00,960 --> 00:01:03,680
if kissing is the language of love,

13
00:01:03,680 --> 00:01:06,040
how about we start a conversation?

14
00:01:06,040 --> 00:01:09,600
Aren’t there already enough languages
for people to reject you?

15
00:01:11,920 --> 00:01:14,560
Now, on to our first story for tonight.

16
00:01:14,960 --> 00:01:18,600
Government authorities have finally
come up with a solution

17
00:01:18,600 --> 00:01:21,240
for the frequent MRT breakdowns...

18
00:01:21,840 --> 00:01:22,800
no, really.

19
00:01:23,240 --> 00:01:25,800
Here’s Bertha Haryani with the report.

20
00:01:25,800 --> 00:01:28,800
The Singapore Trains Department (STD)

21
00:01:28,800 --> 00:01:30,840
has had it with
the constant breakdowns

22
00:01:30,840 --> 00:01:32,920
and its own general inability

23
00:01:32,920 --> 00:01:35,240
to deliver on its most basic service

24
00:01:35,240 --> 00:01:38,040
of getting people
from one place to another

25
00:01:38,040 --> 00:01:42,040
without track faults, train faults,
and signaling interruptions.

26
00:01:42,040 --> 00:01:45,520
Here’s one of the executives
at STD to tell us more.

27
00:01:50,520 --> 00:01:53,200
I am the Chief Transmitter of STD

28
00:01:53,200 --> 00:01:55,160
and also a member of the board.

29
00:01:55,600 --> 00:01:57,560
After an extensive review

30
00:01:57,560 --> 00:02:01,360
of our signaling infrastructure
and aging trains,

31
00:02:01,360 --> 00:02:05,120
we have concluded that
the fault actually lies with…

32
00:02:05,400 --> 00:02:06,440
wait for it…

33
00:02:09,160 --> 00:02:11,400
overuse of the train system.

34
00:02:11,760 --> 00:02:14,040
The network simply isn’t designed

35
00:02:14,040 --> 00:02:17,000
to handle such high ridership.

36
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:19,560
So the board has concluded that

37
00:02:19,560 --> 00:02:22,200
if ridership goes down,

38
00:02:22,200 --> 00:02:24,960
so will the strain on the network,

39
00:02:24,960 --> 00:02:28,200
and hence the frequency
of breakdowns.

40
00:02:32,200 --> 00:02:35,160
The Government Transport
Authority (GTA)

41
00:02:35,160 --> 00:02:38,600
has been working with the STD
to come up with a solution.

42
00:02:38,760 --> 00:02:40,880
And it appears that the solution

43
00:02:40,880 --> 00:02:42,360
is to discourage commuters

44
00:02:42,360 --> 00:02:45,280
from using the train system
in the first place.

45
00:02:45,640 --> 00:02:48,480
As part of an initiative
to discourage commuters

46
00:02:48,480 --> 00:02:50,320
from using the train system,

47
00:02:50,320 --> 00:02:55,200
the board of STD has decided
to raise fares by 500 percent.

48
00:02:55,520 --> 00:02:58,480
A single trip from Ang Mo Kio
to Raffles Place,

49
00:02:58,480 --> 00:03:01,600
which used to cost $1.43,

50
00:03:01,600 --> 00:03:04,840
will now cost $7.15.

51
00:03:05,240 --> 00:03:08,400
Well, all this train breakdowns have really
wasted too much of people’s time,

52
00:03:08,400 --> 00:03:09,800
and time is money.

53
00:03:09,800 --> 00:03:11,200
So from our point of view,

54
00:03:11,200 --> 00:03:13,400
we believe that
raising the fares for the train,

55
00:03:13,400 --> 00:03:15,920
we are actually going to make it
more affordable in the long run.

56
00:03:15,920 --> 00:03:17,520
Now let me qualify my statement.

57
00:03:17,800 --> 00:03:19,800
As we all know the ERP
system very well

58
00:03:19,800 --> 00:03:21,760
and it is also a very good system,

59
00:03:21,760 --> 00:03:24,880
the increase of the train
fares will result in lesser commuters

60
00:03:24,880 --> 00:03:26,600
and therefore lesser breakdowns.

61
00:03:26,600 --> 00:03:28,720
Now in addition, we are also hoping
that this movement

62
00:03:28,720 --> 00:03:31,080
will give the sandwich class a push,

63
00:03:31,080 --> 00:03:32,760
in buying the car that
they have always wanted.

64
00:03:32,760 --> 00:03:35,080
Now that is an absolutely,
great thing, isn't it?

65
00:03:35,720 --> 00:03:36,800
Oh, you don’t know the sandwich class?

66
00:03:36,800 --> 00:03:39,880
They are the kind of people that
will spend $22 on a sandwich.

67
00:03:44,480 --> 00:03:47,200
While the government recognises
that this move

68
00:03:47,200 --> 00:03:49,920
will likely increase
the number of cars on the roads

69
00:03:49,920 --> 00:03:53,760
due to a mad rush by those
in the sandwich class to buy cars,

70
00:03:53,760 --> 00:03:56,040
it maintains that this is the best way

71
00:03:56,040 --> 00:03:58,680
to solve the problem of
frequent breakdowns.

72
00:04:04,160 --> 00:04:07,360
Actually, now that the train fare
is so expensive,

73
00:04:07,880 --> 00:04:10,440
taking the train is very comfortable,

74
00:04:10,440 --> 00:04:12,920
very fast and very efficient.

75
00:04:13,520 --> 00:04:16,400
Just the other day,
I went to the train station

76
00:04:16,400 --> 00:04:17,960
to buy an EZ link card

77
00:04:17,960 --> 00:04:19,640
to try and take the train.

78
00:04:19,640 --> 00:04:21,040
There was no queue,

79
00:04:21,360 --> 00:04:24,000
and in the train, it was very empty.

80
00:04:24,320 --> 00:04:25,440
There was nobody.

81
00:04:26,200 --> 00:04:27,800
With so few riders

82
00:04:28,160 --> 00:04:30,000
and running under capacity,

83
00:04:30,520 --> 00:04:32,560
how to break down?

84
00:04:35,640 --> 00:04:37,920
I used to take the train
to work every day.

85
00:04:38,720 --> 00:04:42,680
But now that it’s almost
as expensive as taking a taxi,

86
00:04:43,080 --> 00:04:45,720
which is almost as expensive
as buying a car,

87
00:04:46,720 --> 00:04:48,320
I might as well buy a car, right?

88
00:04:48,840 --> 00:04:49,720
I mean...

89
00:04:51,080 --> 00:04:52,760
what’s another loan, right?

90
00:04:53,240 --> 00:04:54,040
Home loan,

91
00:04:54,040 --> 00:04:55,160
renovation loan,

92
00:04:55,160 --> 00:04:56,640
personal loan, car loan.

93
00:04:57,520 --> 00:04:59,680
Don’t even know whether
I can finish paying, or not.

94
00:05:00,720 --> 00:05:02,760
I spend way too much on sandwiches.

95
00:05:03,040 --> 00:05:04,080
Which is delicious,

96
00:05:04,760 --> 00:05:06,240
which is fabulicious,

97
00:05:06,800 --> 00:05:09,080
and stylolicious. Do you want?

98
00:05:09,440 --> 00:05:11,760
I tell you, the tuna
comes from cold countries.

99
00:05:11,760 --> 00:05:13,240
You try, ah! Try!

100
00:05:13,240 --> 00:05:14,320
Try, ah.

101
00:05:14,320 --> 00:05:15,760
The government has warned

102
00:05:15,760 --> 00:05:19,600
that COE prices in the
upcoming months will likely increase

103
00:05:19,600 --> 00:05:22,920
due to a higher demand for cars
from the sandwich class.

104
00:05:22,920 --> 00:05:24,280
What’s new, I suppose?

105
00:05:24,640 --> 00:05:26,240
This is Bertha Haryani,

106
00:05:26,240 --> 00:05:28,080
reporting for The Noose.

107
00:05:28,120 --> 00:05:30,800
Good thing I negotiated
for transportation

108
00:05:30,800 --> 00:05:33,280
to be covered in my expat package.

109
00:05:33,280 --> 00:05:34,440
Wait! What?

110
00:05:34,440 --> 00:05:36,320
You got an expat package?

111
00:05:36,320 --> 00:05:37,200
Yes.

112
00:05:37,600 --> 00:05:39,160
We need to talk about this.

113
00:05:40,560 --> 00:05:42,120
On to our next story.

114
00:05:42,520 --> 00:05:45,280
Good-looking spokespeople, like me,

115
00:05:45,280 --> 00:05:47,200
attract the public’s attention.

116
00:05:47,440 --> 00:05:49,800
But as Jacques Ooi finds out,

117
00:05:49,800 --> 00:05:53,080
this strategy has its own pitfalls.

118
00:05:56,120 --> 00:05:57,440
Throughout the ages,

119
00:05:57,440 --> 00:06:01,760
uniformed personnel have always
been considered irresistible,

120
00:06:01,760 --> 00:06:03,360
with their toned bodies,

121
00:06:03,360 --> 00:06:05,200
well-pressed number 1s

122
00:06:05,200 --> 00:06:07,560
and immaculately-groomed faces.

123
00:06:08,240 --> 00:06:10,720
Even emotionless Singaporeans

124
00:06:10,720 --> 00:06:14,080
are not immune to the charms
of handsome policemen,

125
00:06:14,080 --> 00:06:17,080
as evidenced by the popularity of the...

126
00:06:17,640 --> 00:06:21,080
“Shop theft is a crime”
cardboard policeman,

127
00:06:21,080 --> 00:06:24,760
and the rather youthful auxiliary
police officer,

128
00:06:24,760 --> 00:06:28,000
who checks our passports
at Changi Airport.

129
00:06:28,400 --> 00:06:30,480
While Singaporeans are happy

130
00:06:30,480 --> 00:06:33,480
to ogle at these men in blue,

131
00:06:33,480 --> 00:06:35,560
one prominent policeman

132
00:06:35,560 --> 00:06:38,720
is rather worried by this trend

133
00:06:38,720 --> 00:06:41,360
of good-looking spokespeople.

134
00:06:42,360 --> 00:06:44,960
By only focusing on handsome officers,

135
00:06:44,960 --> 00:06:47,120
you are providing the public

136
00:06:47,120 --> 00:06:50,360
with an unrealistic
expectation of policemen.

137
00:06:50,720 --> 00:06:53,920
Just yesterday, I responded to
a noise-disturbance call

138
00:06:53,920 --> 00:06:57,320
that involved a few youngsters
who were creating a ruckus.

139
00:06:57,320 --> 00:06:59,480
And the girl who answered
the door said,

140
00:06:59,480 --> 00:07:01,520
“Hey, Uncle, don’t bluff.

141
00:07:01,520 --> 00:07:03,120
You cannot be policeman."

142
00:07:03,120 --> 00:07:04,600
"Nowadays,” she said,

143
00:07:04,600 --> 00:07:06,480
“all policemen look like Elvin Ng.”

144
00:07:08,600 --> 00:07:11,280
How are we supposed to
do our jobs like that?

145
00:07:11,840 --> 00:07:13,960
Apart from speaking up on the issue,

146
00:07:13,960 --> 00:07:17,800
Sergeant Dollah
has also challenged the YANDAO,

147
00:07:17,800 --> 00:07:21,520
or Young And Attractive Officers union,

148
00:07:21,960 --> 00:07:23,960
to compete against him

149
00:07:23,960 --> 00:07:25,680
in a one-on-one race

150
00:07:25,680 --> 00:07:28,680
during the annual intra-police games.

151
00:07:29,720 --> 00:07:33,440
This is my way of proving that anything
the YANDAO can do,

152
00:07:33,440 --> 00:07:34,600
we can do also.

153
00:07:35,160 --> 00:07:36,760
You know, my dream is...

154
00:07:36,760 --> 00:07:39,720
for the next SFP,
Singapore Frontline Police,

155
00:07:40,320 --> 00:07:41,480
the spokesperson,

156
00:07:42,080 --> 00:07:43,080
he has to have...

157
00:07:43,600 --> 00:07:44,640
a "dad bod".

158
00:07:44,640 --> 00:07:48,640
Did you know that people with
"dad bods" live longer?

159
00:07:49,040 --> 00:07:50,600
This is the body of a man

160
00:07:51,040 --> 00:07:53,680
who tirelessly provides for his family

161
00:07:53,680 --> 00:07:57,280
and caringly eats his childrens’ leftovers

162
00:07:57,280 --> 00:07:59,880
when they complain that
his cooking sucks.

163
00:08:00,400 --> 00:08:01,880
-Yes...
-Come, let's go.

164
00:08:02,360 --> 00:08:03,240
Oh, start already?

165
00:08:03,240 --> 00:08:05,600
Sorry, excuse me,
I have a score to settle.

166
00:08:08,600 --> 00:08:12,760
While netizens have voiced their
support for Sergeant Dollah’s cause,

167
00:08:13,360 --> 00:08:18,480
the SFP is unlikely to change their
handsome-spokesperson tactic.

168
00:08:19,200 --> 00:08:21,400
If you check the
hashtag #shoptheftisacrime,

169
00:08:24,080 --> 00:08:26,040
you will notice that on Instagram,

170
00:08:26,040 --> 00:08:28,920
November last year,
we had 118 posts.

171
00:08:28,920 --> 00:08:32,880
That is 44 more posts than #DFTRch5.

172
00:08:34,080 --> 00:08:35,880
But actually, what is "DFTR"?

173
00:08:36,520 --> 00:08:38,920
But all is not lost for Sergeant Dollah.

174
00:08:38,920 --> 00:08:42,280
The Police Commissioner
will be issuing a statement,

175
00:08:42,280 --> 00:08:45,200
and commending him for his drive
on the intranet,

176
00:08:45,200 --> 00:08:47,000
as well as rewarding him with

177
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:49,960
$20 worth of supermarket vouchers.

178
00:08:50,760 --> 00:08:51,680
Yay.

179
00:08:52,360 --> 00:08:55,480
This is Jacques Ooi,
reporting for The Noose.

